(Urban Heat Islands and Climate Adaptation) Tj
T*
T*
(An urban heat island occurs when a city becomes noticeably warmer than nearby) Tj
T*
(rural areas. Buildings, roads, parking lots, and rooftops absorb solar energy) Tj
T*
(during the day and release it slowly at night. Dense development can also reduce) Tj
T*
(airflow, while vehicles, air conditioners, and industrial equipment add waste) Tj
T*
(heat. The result is a city climate that can remain hot even after sunset. This) Tj
T*
(matters because high nighttime temperatures prevent people from recovering from) Tj
T*
(daytime heat stress.) Tj
T*
T*
(Heat islands are not evenly distributed. Neighborhoods with fewer trees, more) Tj
T*
(pavement, older housing, and limited access to parks often experience higher) Tj
T*
(temperatures. These areas may also have more residents who are elderly, medically) Tj
T*
(vulnerable, or unable to afford air conditioning. Because of this, heat adaptation) Tj
T*
(is both an environmental challenge and a public health challenge. A citywide) Tj
T*
(average temperature can hide dangerous local hot spots.) Tj
T*
T*
(Trees are one of the most effective cooling strategies. They provide shade and) Tj
T*
(cool the air through evapotranspiration, the process by which water moves from) Tj
T*
(soil through plants and into the atmosphere. Street trees can make sidewalks more) Tj
T*
(comfortable and reduce indoor cooling demand when they shade windows and walls.) Tj
T*
(However, tree programs require maintenance, watering, species selection, and) Tj
T*
(community input. Planting a tree is only the beginning; keeping it alive through) Tj
T*
(drought and construction pressure is the harder task.) Tj
T*
T*
